metadata.name: Residents #174
metadata.description:
Hello,
this is my first project here. This token will grant you your own randomly generated 'Resident'.

Features:
- Infinite variations of residents.
- There are 3 color modes you can get: Dull (70%), Bright (25%) and Black & White (5%).
- You can also get 3 different backgrounds: Stripes (50%), Waffles (30%) and Diamonds (20%).
- There is also chance your resident will have his eyelids hald-closed: Opened (75%), Closed (25%).

Interactive Features:
- Eyes are controled with cursor.
- You can toggle palette on and off by mouse-clicking.

metadata.name: 2D Mansion #666
metadata.description:
A mansion generator to crash real estate prices.

Press 'n' or click on the sun to cycle day/night, 's' toggle the canvas resizing and allows to zoom or take a picture at full resolution.

Guest has 7 different values (Two can only happen at a certain moon phase) and there are 4 different materials.

metadata.name: Desert Solitude #31
metadata.description: "Desert Solitude" is an exploration of my love for crystals, architecture, being one with nature, escaping technology and becoming ok with the idea of being alone. The series was derived using diffusion Ai models and put together in a generative image composition on fx(hash) May 2022. 123 editions were made available.

metadata.name: A24Z #280
metadata.description:
Every artist and collector feels the joy of both creating and collecting. But if I could share the joy of creating with collectors. And collectors with their family and friends, what may be an additive process of joy is now perhaps exponential. Joy to the power of 26 to be exact. 

In this work I invite my friends and collectors to collaborate with me. Though not in coding, but together in a process of creating narratives and visuals. Code and story. We didn’t use github, just a simple p5.js editor to try out different programs and palettes. Pedrofe and J0rdan pick their palettes tastefully and carefully. okeoke, perhaps more of a genius than he lets on, picks his palettes blind. No hex color picker. Just straight up rhymes.  

In our discussions verbal language was forbidden. Only emojis were allowed to express our tastes and views. Each emojis put down on google doc was taken with absolutely seriousness. 

Pedro: Loves to taking his daily walks on “Magic Mushroom Mountain”

J0rdan: Wonders about “Quark Question Quiches”

Okeoke: Just get lost in “Finnegans’ Flower Fields.”

It has been a great joy to present our illustration book A24Z, 8 more than you know who. Each page expresses the alphabet with the best of our knowledge in semantics and sarcasm. Collect just 1 page, collect the alphabets that spell out your name, collect the whole A to Z. Read it to your children or loved ones. Though you might need to interpolate or extrapolate with great imagination which children all have. But most importantly, like all children, have fun!

Press 1 to save png, only for Chrome, not Safari. Preview images are compressed or broken, test capture at 300 sec.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Origin-a-tions II: Formation #24
metadata.description:
Nothing stays the same as they first origin-a-ted. Things are constantly changing from one form to another. Only those who can see all these formation steps in order can really grasp the true nature of things.

Origin-a-tions is a three-parts series of generative artwork, started with Part I: Creation and continuing now with Part II: Formation, that depicts one possible variation of how things may be originating.

* * *

20 reserved pieces will be sent as gift to collectors who minted 4 or more pieces of Origin-a-tions I: Creation.

Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
Made with: JavaScript + HTML Canvas
License: LICENSE.txt

In Live-Mode...

...press 's' to save current frame
...click/tap/press space for day/night change

-@TeNinEightNFTs

Created with p5.js using map2.

metadata.name: Herbarium #826
metadata.description:
"Herbarium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Occasionally, I stumble upon vintage scientific illustrations on various topics, exotically looking charts and graphs, alternative layouts for the periodic tables or psychological research diagrams, elaborate illustrations of botany and zoology, minerals, and natural and sometimes unnatural phenomena. Most of those illustrations are part of the "art and science" practices from the 18th and 19th centuries. At the core of those practices were observation and interpretation, unraveling complexity through visualizing abstract ideas or finding a creative approach for understanding previously incomprehensible forms. 

I'm an admirer of two female pioneers in the field. Maria Sibylla Merian created, with immense dedication, a book with intricate illustrations of plants and insects, later praised by scientists. On the other hand, Anna Atkins published a book with beautiful botanical cyanotypes, considered the first book with photographic images. These topics are the visual inspiration for pieces presented at ArtBasel HK. 

My mathematical background makes me naturally attracted to graphs, converting numbers to curves, and everything schematically displayed. Also, combining scientific symbols and illustrations with imaginary data inspires the spectator to find meaning in unrelated or random things or provokes latent skepticism towards assumed concepts of truth, reality, and knowledge.
